Make `next-error` work on '*Shell Command Output*'
	need next-error-select-buffer from GNU Emacs

This editor badly needs a quick-fix mode like "vi -q" and it's already
got MOST of what it needs to implement it.  Why can't you populate the
"next-error" [sic] buffer from a command-line option?  All kinds of
commands at long last produce GCC-diagnostic-style output, including
grep.  The ability to use that output to drive an editor session is
(or should be!) within easy reach.

Should `join-line` take its argument more literally?  What does GNU
Emacs do?

Why isn't the cscope buffer in a form useful for "next-error"?

Missing directory, create?  XXX and if that fails?

Migrate from "prefix-region" to "set-fill-prefix" (GNU Emacs)

De-optimize for 110 and 300 baud terminal connections, which were still
a thing when MicroEmacs was written.  Hence the laconic, and confusing,
"Quit" traditionally spat at the emacs user.  On the bright side, that
repeated stentorian utterance, misinterpreted as an imperative, likely
drove uptake of vi.  (Maybe it was intended to.)  Diagnostic messages
must express clear ideas, employing editor jargon only where necessary,
and never using terminology that appears only in editor source code.

More ambitious stuff
--------------------

* DYNAMIC ABBREVIATION MODE.  This is a killer feature.  (It took too
  long to get to the vi world, but finally made it.)

* What's the backup/autosave story?  Can you call yourself a serious
  text editor without these features?  You should always be able to
  write all open buffers (if modified).  Do any editors speculatively
  write to the disk to see if a starvation situation is approaching, and
  warn the user?  What strategies do they use?

* Use XDG_CONFIG_HOME for storage of precious temporaries and autosaved
  files, and for the existing log feature (see below).

* Steal nano's idea for help lines for commonly used bindings. (Because
  I am old, I vaguely recollect that, in cruder form, this may have
  been a feature of WordStar, which troglobit-mg seems to imitate.)
  Copy nano's smartness: the more screen real estate it has, the more
  bindings it shows you.  As nano implements it, this feature is more
  helpful to users with crazily wide terminal windows than to everyone
  else.  So make the height configurable (in terms of screen lines? or
  percentage of terminal window height?).

* Link with full-on curses and ncurses's panel library.  Use that to
  enable pop-up windows for diagnostics from the minibuffer, which right
  now are badly constrained in terms of space and overwrite the
  immediate context, which is harshly user-hostile.  Make any such
  pop-up window:

  - semi-modal
  - resizable
  - movable

  ...because inevitably, the pop-up will overlay a buffer window
  containing material the user needs to keep visible to decide their
  next action.

* Recursive edits, with named stack entries to remind you what the hell
  you where working on when you got sidetracked.

* Use the logging feature to statistically measure the time delay before
  each binding the user employs.  A short delay means the user knows the
  command and doesn't need it on the nano-esque help lines.  Combined
  with a per-binding population count, that may be all we need.  We
  could rank the items in the help lines by the product of the
  population count and the pre-stroke delay.  A command that is
  frequently used but also frequently dithered before is one the user
  wants/needs help remembering.
